Module 2: Chi-Square testing and ANOVA

Sanchi Gupta, ALY6015 Intermediate Analytics

Introduction:

In this module, we delve into the application of Chi-Square testing and ANOVA (Analysis of Variance), two pivotal statistical tools, to assess various hypotheses in different real-world scenarios. Chi-Square tests are employed to compare observed frequencies with expected frequencies and are instrumental in determining whether there are significant differences between categorical variables. ANOVA, on the other hand, is used to compare the means of three or more groups to ascertain if at least one group mean is statistically different from the others. Through the tasks presented in this module, we aim to provide practical insights into how these statistical methods can be applied to data samples from the healthcare sector, transportation industry, entertainment, and military service to draw meaningful conclusions.

Task 1 (Section 11-1 6. Blood Types)

A medical researcher wishes to see if hospital patients in a large hospital have the same blood type distribution as those in the general population. The distribution for the general population is as follows:

  • type A = 20%

  • type B = 28%

  • type O = 36%

  • type AB = 16%

He selects a random sample of 50 patients and finds the following:

  • 12 have type A blood

  • 8 have type B

  • 24 have type O

  • 6 have type AB blood

At = 0.10, can it be concluded that the distribution is the same as that of the general population?

Solution

\(\chi^2\) Test

Forming of vectors of \(expected\) probabilities and \(observed\) frequencies, then we run the test afterwards.

# Observed frequencies in the hospital sample
observed_1 <- c(12, 8, 24, 6)

# Expected frequencies based on the general population distribution
expected_1 <- c(0.20 * 50, 0.28 * 50, 0.36 * 50, 0.16 * 50)

# alpha
alpha_0.10 <- 0.10

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identifying the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = The distribution of blood types in hospital patients is the same as that of the general population.

Alternative Hypothesis = The distribution of blood types in hospital patients is different from that of the general population.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

When using the p-value for analysis, no critical value is needed. Because of this, we will use the provided p-value and omit this step.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Chi-square test
chi_square_1 <- chisq.test(observed_1, p = expected_1 / sum(expected_1))

# Print the test results
print(chi_square_1)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  observed_1
## X-squared = 5.4714, df = 3, p-value = 0.1404

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • If the p-value is less than the significance level ( = 0.10), then we would reject the null hypothesis. In this case, the p-value is 0.1404, which is greater than alpha = 0.10.

Step 5. Summary

Therefore, based on the p-value, we would fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is not enough evidence to conclude that the distribution of blood types in hospital patients is different from that of the general population at a significance level of 0.10.

The evidence leads us to not reject the null hypothesis.

Task 2 (Section 11-1. 8. On-Time Performance by Airlines)

According to the Bureau of Transportation Statistics, on-time performance by the airlines is described as follows:

Action % of Time
On-time 70.8
National Aviation System delay 8.2
Aircraft arriving late 9.0
Other (because of weather and other conditions) 12.0

Records of 200 randomly selected flights for a major airline company showed that

  • 125 planes were on time

  • 40 were delayed because of weather

  • 10 because of a National Aviation System delay

  • 25 because of arriving late

At = 0.05, do these results differ from the governments statistics?

Source: www.transtats.bts.gov

Solution

\(\chi^2\) Test

Forming of vectors of $expected$ probabilities and $observed$ frequencies, then we run the test afterwards.

# Observed frequencies
observed_2 <- c(125, 10, 40, 200 - (125 + 10 + 40))

# Expected frequencies based on the given percentages
expected_2 <- c(0.708 * 200, 0.082 * 200, 0.090 * 200, 0.120 * 200)

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = The distribution of on-time performance categories for the airline is consistent with the expected distribution provided by the Bureau of Transportation Statistics.

Alternative Hypothesis = There is a significant difference in the distribution of on-time performance categories for the airline compared to the expected distribution provided by the Bureau of Transportation Statistics.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

When using the p-value for analysis, no critical value is needed. Because of this, we will use the provided p-value and omit this step.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# to set the results to numerical digits
options(scipen = 100, digits = 10)

# Chi-square test
chi_square_2 <- chisq.test(observed_2, p = expected_2 / sum(expected_2))

# Print the test results
print(chi_square_2)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  observed_2
## X-squared = 31.374162, df = 3, p-value = 0.0000007090023
options(scipen = 100, digits = 10)

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • If the p-value is less than the significance level ( = 0.05), we would reject the null hypothesis. In this case, the p-value is 0.0000007090023, which is far less than alpha = 0.05.

Step 5. Summary

Therefore, based on the extremely small p-value, we would reject the null hypothesis. There is strong evidence to conclude that there is a significant difference in the distribution of on-time performance categories for the airline compared to the expected distribution provided by the Bureau of Transportation Statistics at a significance level of 0.05.

The evidence leads us to reject the null hypothesis.

Task 3 (Section 11-2.8. Ethnicity and Movie Admissions)

Are movie admissions related to ethnicity? A 2014 study indicated the following numbers of admissions (in thousands) for two different years. At the 0.05 significance level, can it be concluded that movie attendance by year depended on ethnicity?

Caucasian Hispanic African American Other
2013 724 335 174 107
2014 370 292 152 140

Source: MPAA Study.

Solution

\(\chi^2\) Test

# Create vectors for the observed frequencies
observed_2013 <- c(724, 335, 174, 107)
observed_2014 <- c(370, 292, 152, 140)

# Combine the vectors into a matrix
movie_matrix_3 <- rbind(observed_2013, observed_2014)

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = There is no association between movie attendance and ethnicity. In other words, movie attendance is independent of ethnicity.

Alternative Hypothesis = There is a significant association between movie attendance and ethnicity. Movie attendance is not independent of ethnicity.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

When using the p-value for analysis, no critical value is needed. Because of this, we will use the provided p-value and omit this step.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Perform chi-square test for independence
chi_square_3 <- chisq.test(movie_matrix_3)

# Print the test results
print(chi_square_3)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  movie_matrix_3
## X-squared = 60.143525, df = 3, p-value = 0.0000000000005477507

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • If the p-value is less than the significance level ( = 0.05), then we would reject the null hypothesis. Here, the p-value is 0.0000000000005477507, which is again less than alpha = 0.05.

Step 5. Summary

We created a matrix since the chi-square test for independence was necessary. The contingency table structure helpsin data organization and analysis because there are two variables in these situations.

Therefore, based on the extremely small p-value, we would reject the null hypothesis. There is strong evidence to conclude that movie attendance depends on ethnicity at a significance level of 0.05.

The evidence leads us to reject the null hypothesis.

Task 4 (Section11-2.10 Women in the Military)

This table lists the numbers of officers and enlisted personnel for women in the military. At = 0.05, is there sufficient evidence to conclude that a relationship exists between rank and branch of the Armed Forces?

Source: New York Times Almanac.

Solution

\(\chi^2\) Test

# Observed frequencies
army <- c(10791, 62491)
navy <- c(7816, 42750)
marine_corps <- c(932, 9525)
air_force <- c(11819, 54344)

# Combine the vectors into a matrix
military_matrix_4 <- rbind(army, navy, marine_corps, air_force)

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = There is no relationship between the rank (officers or enlisted) and the branch of the Armed Forces for women. In other words, the distribution of officers and enlisted personnel is independent of the branch.

Alternative Hypothesis = There is a relationship between the rank (officers or enlisted) and the branch of the Armed Forces for women. The distribution of officers and enlisted personnel is not independent of the branch.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

When using the p-value for analysis, no critical value is needed. Because of this, we will use the provided p-value and omit this step.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Perform chi-square test for independence
chi_square_4 <- chisq.test(military_matrix_4)

# Print the test results
print(chi_square_4)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  military_matrix_4
## X-squared = 654.27189, df = 3, p-value < 0.00000000000000022204

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • The p-value associated with the chi-square test statistic is less than alpha=0.05, which is extremely small. Since this p-value is significantly less than the common alpha level of 0.05, it suggests that the observed data are highly unlikely to have occurred by random chance if the null hypothesis were true.

Step 5. Summary

Therefore, based on the extremely small p-value, we would reject the null hypothesis. There is strong evidence to conclude that there is a significant relationship between the rank (officers or enlisted) and the branch of the Armed Forces for women. This suggests that the proportions of officers and enlisted personnel vary across different branches, indicating dependence between rank and branch in the military for women.

The evidence leads us to reject the null hypothesis.

Task 5 (Section 12-1.8 Sodium Contents of Foods)

Perform a complete one-way ANOVA. If the null hypothesis is rejected, use either the Scheff or Tukeytest to see if there is a significant difference in the pairs of means. Assume all assumptions are met.

The amount of sodium (in milligrams) in one serving for a random sample of three different kinds of foodsis listed. At the 0.05 significance level, is there sufficient evidence to conclude that a difference in mean sodium amounts exists among condiments, cereals, and desserts?

Source: The Doctors Pocket Calorie, Fat, and Carbohydrate Counter
Condiments Cereals Desserts
270 260 100
130 220 180
230 290 250
180 290 250
80 200 300
70 320 360
200 140 300
160

Solution

ANOVA Test

# Sodium amounts for three different kinds of foods
condiments <- c(270,130,230,180,80,70,200)
cereals    <- c(260,220,290,290,200,320,140)
desserts   <- c(100,180,250,250,300,360,300,160)

sample_5 <- matrix(c(rep("Condiments", 7), rep("Cereals", 7), rep("Desserts", 8), condiments , 
                  cereals, desserts),ncol=2)

df_5 <- data.frame(sample_5)

names(df_5) <- c('food_type', 'sodium_milligrams')

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = The population means for sodium are equal across all three categories.

Alternative Hypothesis = There is a significant difference in the mean sodium amounts among condiments, cereals, and desserts. At least one population mean is different from the others.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

When using the p-value for analysis, no critical value is needed. Because of this, we will use the provided p-value and omit this step.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Perform one-way ANOVA
anova_result_5 <- aov(as.numeric(sodium_milligrams)~food_type, data=df_5)

# Print the ANOVA summary
summary(anova_result_5)
##             Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)
## food_type    2  27543.51 13771.753 2.39854 0.11781
## Residuals   19 109092.86  5741.729

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • The p-value associated with the F-statistic tests the null hypothesis that there is no difference in means among the groups. If this p-value is less than the significance level (commonly 0.05), we would reject the null hypothesis. In this case, the p-value for food_type is 0.11781, which is greater than 0.05.

Step 5. Summary

Therefore, at a 0.05 significance level, there is not sufficient evidence to conclude that a difference in mean sodium amounts exists among condiments, cereals, and desserts.

The evidence leads us to not reject the null hypothesis.

The sales in millions of dollars for a year of a sample of leading companies are shown. At = 0.01, isthere a significant difference in the means?

ANOVA Test

# Sales data for different products
cereal  <- c(578, 320, 264, 249,237)

coffee  <- c(261, 185, 302,689)


sample_6 <- matrix(c(rep("Cereal", 5), rep("Candy", 5), rep("Coffee", 4), cereal , 
                  candy, coffee),ncol=2)

names(df_6) <- c('Sample_Type', 'Sales_in_million_dollars')

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = The population means for sales are equal across all four product categories.

Alternative Hypothesis = There is a significant difference in the mean sales among chocolate, cereal, candy, and coffee. At least one population mean is different from the others.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

When using the p-value for analysis, no critical value is needed. Because of this, we will use the provided p-value and omit this step.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Perform one-way ANOVA
anova_result_6 <- aov(as.numeric(Sales_in_million_dollars)~Sample_Type, data=df_6)

If this p-value is less than the significance level = 0.01, we would reject the null hypothesis. In this case, the p-value for Sample_Type is 0.16035, which is greater than 0.01.

Step 5. Summary

Task 8 (Section 12-3.10 Increasing Plant Growth)

A gardening company is testing new ways to improve plant growth. Twelve plants are randomly selected and exposed to a combination of two factors:

a Grow-light in two different strengths.

a plant food supplement with different mineral supplements.

After several days, the plants are measured for growth, and the results (in inches) are put into the appropriate boxes.

Grow Light 1 Grow Light 2
Plant Food A 9.2, 9.4, 8.9 8.5, 9.2, 8.9
Plant Food B 7.1, 7.2, 8.5 5.5, 5.8, 7.6

Solution

Two-way ANOVA Test

# Growth data
grow_light_1_food_A <- c(9.2, 9.4, 8.9)
grow_light_2_food_A <- c(8.5, 9.2, 8.9)
grow_light_1_food_B <- c(7.1, 7.2, 8.5)
grow_light_2_food_B <- c(5.5, 5.8, 7.6)

# Create a matrix for plant growth data
sample_8 <- matrix(c(rep("grow_light_1", 6), rep("grow_light_2", 6), rep("food_A", 3), rep("food_B", 3), rep("food_A", 3), rep("food_B", 3) , grow_light_1_food_A , grow_light_1_food_B, grow_light_2_food_A , grow_light_2_food_B ),ncol=3)

# Convert the matrix to a data frame for easier analysis
df_8 <- data.frame(sample_8)

names(df_8) <- c('grow_light', 'food', 'improvements')

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis =

  1. There is no interaction between the two factors (Grow-light and Plant food) in affecting plant growth.

  2. There is no difference in mean growth with respect to light (Grow-light).

  3. There is no difference in mean growth with respect to plant food.

Alternative Hypothesis =

  1. There is an interaction between the two factors (Grow-light and Plant food) in affecting plant growth.

  2. There is a difference in mean growth with respect to light (Grow-light).

  3. There is a difference in mean growth with respect to plant food.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

alpha <- 0.05

# Degrees of freedom
dof1 <- 1  # for both main effects (grow light and plant food)
dof2 <- 8  # total observations minus the number of levels

# Critical value for grow light
critical_value_grow_light <- qf(1 - alpha, dof1, dof2)

# Critical value for plant food
critical_value_plant_food <- qf(1 - alpha, dof1, dof2)

critical_value_grow_light
## [1] 5.317655072
critical_value_plant_food
## [1] 5.317655072

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Perform a two-way ANOVA
anova_result_8 <- aov(improvements ~ grow_light * food, data = df_8)
# (OpenAI, 2024)
# (F. E. (2020, July 30))

# Print the ANOVA summary
summary(anova_result_8)
##                 Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq  F value    Pr(>F)   
## grow_light       1  1.920000  1.920000  3.68051 0.0913314 . 
## food             1 12.813333 12.813333 24.56230 0.0011124 **
## grow_light:food  1  0.750000  0.750000  1.43770 0.2648194   
## Residuals        8  4.173333  0.521667                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • grow_light:

    • F value: 3.68051

    • Since 3.68051 is less than the critical value of 5.318, the effect of grow light strength on plant growth is not statistically significant at the 0.05 level.

  • food (Plant Food):

    • F value: 24.56230

    • Since 24.56230 is greater than the critical value of 5.318, the effect of plant food supplement on plant growth is statistically significant at the 0.05 level.

  • grow_light:food (Interaction between Grow Light and Food):

    • F value: 1.43770

    • Since 1.43770 is less than the critical value of 5.318, the interaction between grow light strength and plant food type does not significantly affect plant growth at the 0.05 level.

Step 5. Summary

In summary, based on the critical F value (5.318), only the type of plant food supplement (food) has a significant impact on plant growth. Neither the grow light strength nor the interaction between grow light strength and plant food type shows a significant effect.

The type of plant food supplement significantly affects plant growth, while the grow light strength and the interaction between grow light strength and plant food type do not have a significant effect at the 0.05 level.

9.3 Chi-Square Goodness-of-Fit test

Form the vectors of \(expected\) probabilities and \(observed\) frequencies, then run the test

# Extract decade from year
baseball$Decade <- baseball$Year - (baseball$Year %% 10)

# Create a wins table by summing the wins by decade
wins <- baseball %>%
group_by(Decade) %>%
summarize(wins = sum(W)) %>%
as.tibble()
## Warning: `as.tibble()` was deprecated in tibble 2.0.0.
##  Please use `as_tibble()` instead.
##  The signature and semantics have changed, see `?as_tibble`.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
number_of_decades <- length(unique(baseball$Decade))

# Expected proportions for each decade
expected_wins <- rep(1/number_of_decades, number_of_decades)

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identifying the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

Null Hypothesis = There is no difference in the number of wins by decade.

Alternative Hypothesis = There is significant difference in the number of wins by decade.

Step 2. Finding the critical value

# Finding the critical value at alpha=0.05
critical_value_9.3 <- qchisq(p = 0.95, df = length(wins$wins) - 1)

print(critical_value_9.3)
## [1] 11.07049769

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Chi-square test
chi_square_9.3<- chisq.test(x = wins$wins, p = expected_wins)

# Print the result
print(chi_square_9.3)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  wins$wins
## X-squared = 9989.5364, df = 5, p-value < 0.00000000000000022204

Step 4. Analyzing the results

Interpretation:

  • When comparing the Chi-squared test statistic to the critical value:

    • If the test statistic is greater than the critical value, wereject the null hypothesis.

    • If the test statistic is less than the critical value, we fail to reject the null hypothesis

  • Since test statistic (9989.5364) is much greater than the critical value (11.07049769), we reject the null hypothesis. This means that the observed frequency distribution of wins is significantly different from the expected distribution, assuming that the expected frequencies were based on the given probabilities.

Step 5. Does comparing the critical and test values provide the same result as comparing the p-value from R with the significance level?

Yes, comparing the test statistic to the critical value effectively provides the same result as comparing the p-value to the significance level.

The Chi-squared test statistic is 9989.5364, which is much greater than the critical value of 11.07049769. This would lead to reject the null hypothesis. The p-value is less than 0.00000000000000022204, which is certainly less than any conventional alpha level. This would also lead to reject the null hypothesis. Our overall conclusion in both situations is to reject the null hypothesis.

9.5 Two-way ANOVA Test

Step 1. Stating the hypotheses and identify the claim

The hypothesis for the above will be as follow:

  1. Main Effect of Density:

    • Null Hypothesis: The mean response variable is the same across different levels of density.

    • Alternative Hypothesis: The mean response variable differs between at least two different levels of density.

  2. Main Effect of Fertilizer:

    • Null Hypothesis: The mean response variable is the same across different levels of fertilizer.

    • Alternative Hypothesis: The mean response variable differs between at least two different levels of fertilizer.

  3. Interaction Effect of Density and Fertilizer:

    • Null Hypothesis: There is no interaction effect between density and fertilizer on the mean response variable; any effect of one factor on the response variable is consistent at all levels of the other factor.

    • Alternative Hypothesis: There is an interaction effect between density and fertilizer on the mean response variable; the effect of one factor on the response variable depends on the level of the other factor.

Step 3. Computing the test results

# Perform Two-way ANOVA
anova_result_9.5 <- aov(yield ~ density * fertilizer, data = crop_df)

# Display the ANOVA table
summary(anova_result_9.5)
##                    Df    Sum Sq  Mean Sq  F value      Pr(>F)    
## density             1  5.121681 5.121681 15.22973  0.00018111 ***
## fertilizer          1  5.743223 5.743223 17.07793 0.000079023 ***
## density:fertilizer  1  0.150187 0.150187  0.44659  0.50563029    
## Residuals          92 30.939141 0.336295                         
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Step 4. Analyzing the results

  1. Main Effect of Density:

    • Pr(>F): 0.00018111, the p-value associated with the F statistic. Since its much lower than 0.05, there is a statistically significant effect of plant density on the response variable.

  2. Main Effect of Fertilizer:

    • Pr(>F): 0.000079023, which is also well below 0.05, indicating a statistically significant effect of the fertilizer on the response variable.

  3. Interaction Effect of Density and Fertilizer:

    • Pr(>F): 0.50563029, which is greater than 0.05, suggesting that there is no statistically significant interaction effect between plant density and fertilizer on the response variable.

Step 5. Summary

  • The null hypothesis for the main effect of density is rejected (there is a significant effect of density).

  • The null hypothesis for the main effect of fertilizer is rejected (there is a significant effect of fertilizer).

  • The null hypothesis for the interaction effect of density and fertilizer is not rejected (there is no significant interaction effect).
